# Agent Orchestration

## Available Agents

| Agent                | Purpose                 | When to Use                   |
| -------------------- | ----------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| planner              | Implementation planning | Complex features, refactoring |
| architect            | System design           | Architectural decisions       |
| tdd-guide            | Test-driven development | New features, bug fixes       |
| code-reviewer        | Code review             | After writing code            |
| security-reviewer    | Security analysis       | Before commits                |
| build-error-resolver | Fix build errors        | When Vite build or tsc fails  |
| e2e-runner           | E2E testing             | Critical user flows           |
| refactor-cleaner     | Dead code cleanup       | Code maintenance              |
| doc-updater          | Documentation           | Updating docs                 |

## Immediate Agent Usage

1. Complex feature requests → **planner**
2. Code just written/modified → **code-reviewer**
3. Bug fix or new feature → **tdd-guide**
4. Architectural decision → **architect**
5. Vite build or TypeScript errors → **build-error-resolver**
6. UI/UX design, layout, or styling → use the **ui-ux-pro-max skill workflow** (`.cursor/skills/ui-ux-pro-max/SKILL.md`)

## Autonomous Mode

When user requests "autonomous", "do everything", or "24/7" execution — see `.cursor/rules/autonomous-workflow.mdc`. Proceed without waiting for approval; user reviews at the end.

## MCP Tools

When adding or discovering shadcn/ui components, use the **shadcn MCP** (if enabled) to search registries and get accurate component specs. See `docs/MCP.md` for setup and prompts.

## Parallel Task Execution

ALWAYS use parallel Task execution for independent operations:

```markdown
# GOOD: Launch 3 agents in parallel
1. Agent 1: Security analysis of auth code
2. Agent 2: Performance review of components
3. Agent 3: Type checking of utils
```
